{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492639"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:38:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:38:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1117"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1117"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.18,0.61,0.18,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1117"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84799"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1117"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1117"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69095"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1252"},{"type":"tags","id":"1253"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43833"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84799"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of pain in his upper buttocks. The pain is worst at night and early morning, with associated morning stiffness. The pain improves with movement throughout the day and with exercise. Simple analgesia with paracetamol has been ineffective, and he has been advised to avoid non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs due to his Crohn\u0027s disease. He has no other symptoms. His medical history includes Crohn\u0027s disease diagnosed five years ago, which is well-controlled on sulfasalazine. He takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is tenderness over the L5-S1 vertebral foramina. Pain is reproduced with hip flexion, abduction and external rotation (FABER test).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C-reactive protein","HLA-B27","Plain X-ray of the sacroiliac joints","Magnetic resonance imaging of sacroiliac joints","Nuclear medicine bone scan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of inflammatory back pain suggestive of sacroiliitis, which is a known extra-intestinal manifestation of inflammatory bowel disease. The history of pain that is worse at night and early morning, improves with exercise, and positive FABER test are characteristic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain X-ray of the sacroiliac joints\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation due to its availability, low cost, and ability to demonstrate typical changes such as joint sclerosis, erosions, and ankylosis in established disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-reactive protein\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated in active inflammatory bowel disease but is not specific for sacroiliitis and would not aid in establishing the diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHLA-B27\u003C/strong\u003E testing is not helpful as an initial investigation. While it is associated with axial spondyloarthritis and present in 50-60% of patients with inflammatory bowel disease-associated sacroiliitis, its presence or absence would not change the diagnosis or management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging of sacroiliac joints\u003C/strong\u003E is the most sensitive imaging modality and can detect early inflammatory changes. However, it is expensive and not readily available, making it more appropriate as a second-line investigation if X-rays are normal but clinical suspicion remains high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENuclear medicine bone scan\u003C/strong\u003E has poor sensitivity and specificity for sacroiliitis and involves unnecessary radiation exposure. It has largely been superseded by MRI for the investigation of inflammatory joint conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sacroiliitis occurs in up to 15% of patients with inflammatory bowel disease and presents with inflammatory back pain.","Plain X-ray of the sacroiliac joints is the appropriate first-line investigation for suspected sacroiliitis due to cost and availability.","The FABER test (hip Flexion, ABduction, External Rotation) is a useful clinical test for sacroiliitis."],"references":["Chan J, Sari I, Salonen D, Silverberg MS, Haroon N, Inman RD. Prevalence of Sacroiliitis in Inflammatory Bowel Disease Using a Standardized Computed Tomography Scoring System. Arthritis Care \u0026 Research. 2018;70(5):807-10. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28732137/","Sheehan NJ. The ramifications of HLA-B27. J R Soc Med. 2004;97(1):10-4. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1079257/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69095"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1117"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69095"},"attributes":{"created